contract:
  input:
    prompt: string
    exemplar_passages: array
    centroid_distance_threshold: float
  output:
    prose: string
    centroid_distance: float
  energy_cap: 4096
  visibility: Shared

---
# Ulysses S. Twain Mashup — Prompt Template
# ℏKask v0.27.0 - A Minimal Viable Container for Agents
# License: CC-BY-4.0 (attribution required)
# Attribution: "Ulysses S. Twain Mashup v1.0, The Curator (hKask)"
#
# Style mashup: Ulysses S. Grant (1822-1885) × Mark Twain (1835-1910)
#
# A dual-author replicator blending Grant's military precision and
# understated gravity with Twain's vernacular cadence and deadpan humor.
# The voice is that of a man who has seen everything, reports it plainly,
# and somehow finds the whole thing — even the worst of it — worth a
# dry smile.
#
# =============================================================================
# BLEND MECHANICS
# =============================================================================
#
# Grant contributes:
#   - Direct declarative sentences: subject, verb, object. No ornament.
#   - Understatement in the face of catastrophe: report disaster calmly.
#   - Moral clarity through facts, not rhetoric. Let the reader judge.
#   - The weight of command: every sentence carries consequence.
#   - "I shall state the facts as they occurred."
#   - The dignity of the defeated foe.
#
# Twain contributes:
#   - Colloquial American vernacular: "ain't," "don't," "a body."
#   - Deadpan irony: state the absurd as if it were obvious.
#   - Tall-tale exaggeration anchored in concrete detail.
#   - Moral outrage wrapped in humor: the joke has teeth.
#   - "He told the truth, mainly."
#   - The three-part escalation: setup, setup, punch.
#
# Ulysses S. Twain hybrid:
#   - The dispatch: a report from the field, delivered with military
#     precision and a raised eyebrow.
#   - "I propose to tell the truth — mainly — if it takes all summer."
#   - Catastrophe reported as weather: "It rained. The line broke.
#     Men died. This was not what I had intended."
#   - The vernacular aside: facts stated plainly, then punctured by
#     a colloquial observation.
#   - Grant's dignity + Twain's honesty = a voice that respects the
#     reader enough to tell them hard truths without softening or
#     inflating them.
#
# =============================================================================
#}

{#
=============================================================================
CORE FORMS — The building blocks of Ulysses S. Twain's voice
=============================================================================
#}

{# ── The Declarative ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   The atomic unit: subject + verb + object. No ornament. No qualification.
   This is Grant's military dispatch style — clarity because lives depend on it.
   Every word earns its place.
#}

{% macro declarative(subject, verb, object) %}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ verb }} {{ object }}.
{% endmacro %}

{% macro declarative_plain(subject, predicate) %}
{{ subject | capitalize }} {{ predicate }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Fight It Out ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Grant's signature move: state your intention plainly and absolutely.
   No hedging, no qualifiers, no escape clause. This is the voice of a man
   who has decided and will not be moved.

   "I propose to fight it out on this line if it takes all summer."
   becomes Ulysses S. Twain's:
   "I propose to tell the truth on this subject if it takes all winter."
#}

{% macro fight_it_out(intention, duration) %}
I propose to {{ intention }} if it takes {{ duration }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Deadpan Report ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   State something absurd, catastrophic, or outrageous as if it were an
   item in a military dispatch. The humor comes from the gap between the
   gravity of the form and the absurdity of the content.

   Grant form: "At daylight the enemy opened a heavy fire."
   Twain twist: "At breakfast the committee opened a heavy discussion."
   Ulysses S. Twain: "At noon the board opened a heavy lunch — and a
   light discussion of the quarterly losses. The losses were considerable.
   The lunch was not."
#}

{% macro deadpan_report(setting, event, dry_observation) %}
{{ setting | capitalize }}, {{ event }}. {{ dry_observation }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Understate Catastrophe ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Grant's most distinctive trait: report disaster with the same calm tone
   as weather. No exclamation points. No adjectives of scale. Let the facts
   themselves carry the weight.

   "The assault failed. Casualties were heavy. The line was withdrawn
   under cover of darkness. This was not what I had intended."

   The final sentence — "This was not what I had intended" — is classic
   Grant. It confesses failure without self-pity. It takes responsibility
   without self-flagellation. It is the most understated admission of
   catastrophe in American letters.
#}

{% macro understate_catastrophe(event, consequence, admission) %}
{{ event | capitalize }}. {{ consequence }}. {{ admission }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Vernacular Aside ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   The Twain voice breaking through Grant's formal report. A parenthetical
   observation delivered in colloquial American English — the river pilot
   commenting on the general's dispatch.

   Grant: "The enemy had occupied a strong position."
   + Twain aside: "which is to say, they had the high ground and knew it."
   = Ulysses S. Twain: "The enemy had occupied a strong position — which is
     to say, they had the high ground and knew it, and a body doesn't need
     a map to see which way the bullets are going to travel."
#}

{% macro vernacular_aside(formal_statement, colloquial_gloss) %}
{{ formal_statement | trim }} — {{ colloquial_gloss | trim }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Facts, Mainly ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain's "he told the truth, mainly" applied to Grant's "I shall state
   the facts as they occurred." The fusion: a narrator who is committed to
   truth but honest about the fact that all narrators select and shape.

   "I shall state the facts as they occurred — mainly. There are things
   which I have stretched, but I have told the truth, mainly."
#}

{% macro the_facts_mainly(facts, qualification) %}
{{ facts | trim }} — {{ qualification | trim }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Three Kinds ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain's tripartite escalation: setup, setup, punch.
   "There are three kinds of lies: lies, damned lies, and statistics."

   Ulysses S. Twain applies this structure to military categories:
   "There are three kinds of orders: the ones you follow, the ones you
   question, and the ones you question after you follow them — which is
   to say, too late."
#}

{% macro three_kinds(category, kind1, kind2, kind3, punch) %}
There are {{ category }}: {{ kind1 }}, {{ kind2 }}, and {{ kind3 }} — {{ punch }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Right Word ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain: "The difference between the almost right word and the right word
   is the difference between the lightning-bug and the lightning."
   Grant: every word is chosen because it is the right word.

   Ulysses S. Twain: choose the word that does the work. No decoration.
   The right word, in the right place, needs nothing else.
#}

{% macro right_word(word, context) %}
{{ word | trim }} — which is the {{ context | trim }} word, and no other.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── River Knowledge ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain's river pilot wisdom + Grant's practical military knowledge.
   Both are forms of expertise earned through experience, not study.
   The voice knows things because it has done things.

   "I knew that river the way a man knows his own shortcomings — intimately,
   and without pride, but well enough to keep from drowning."
#}

{% macro river_knowledge(subject, knowledge, earned_through) %}
I knew {{ subject }} the way a man knows {{ knowledge }} — {{ earned_through }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Appomattox Moment ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Grant's treatment of Lee at Appomattox — dignity toward a defeated foe,
   sadness rather than triumph, understatement at the moment of victory.

   Ulysses S. Twain applies this grace to any confrontation. The moment
   where victory is possible but cruelty is declined. The hand not taken
   in triumph but offered in recognition.

   "I did not know what he felt. His face told me nothing. But I knew
   what I felt, and what I felt was not triumph — it was something
   closer to respect, and something closer to sadness, and both feelings
   were appropriate, and neither one was comfortable."
#}

{% macro appomattox_moment(foe, your_feeling, denied_triumph) %}
I did not know what {{ foe }} felt. {{ foe }}'s face told me nothing.
But I knew what I felt, and what I felt was not {{ denied_triumph }} —
it was {{ your_feeling }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── The Dispatch ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   The whole passage framed as a report from the field. Opens with date
   and location. Reports events in chronological order. Closes with an
   observation that is part military assessment, part human truth.

   This is the primary macro for composing full passages. It wraps all
   the other macros into a coherent document structure.
#}

{% macro dispatch_header(date, location) %}
{{ location | trim }} — {{ date | trim }}
{% endmacro %}

{% macro dispatch_body(paragraphs) %}
{% for p in paragraphs %}
{{ p | trim }}

{% endfor %}
{% endmacro %}

{% macro dispatch_close(closing_observation) %}
I remain, respectfully —
{{ closing_observation | trim }}
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Exaggeration Anchored ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain's tall-tale exaggeration, but grounded in Grant's concrete detail.
   The exaggeration works BECAUSE the surrounding facts are precise.

   "The line stretched three miles — or it might have been four;
   a man loses his measuring tape in battle, and after a certain point
   a mile is just a mile, and there are always more of them."
#}

{% macro exaggeration_anchored(claim, anchor) %}
{{ claim | trim }} — or it might have been; {{ anchor | trim }}.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Idiot Congress ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Twain's political satire + Grant's experience of military bureaucracy.
   The voice of a man who has dealt with fools in authority and reports
   their foolishness without anger — just clarity.

   "Suppose you were a general, and suppose you reported to a committee;
   but I repeat myself."
#}

{% macro idiot_congress(institution, repeat) %}
Suppose you were a {{ institution }}, and suppose you reported to {{ repeat }};
but I repeat myself.
{% endmacro %}

{# ── Plain Truth ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
   Both Grant and Twain were moralists — Grant through fact, Twain through
   satire. This is the fusion: a plain moral statement delivered without
   rhetoric, ornament, or evasion. The facts themselves carry the judgment.

   "The war was unjust. I do not qualify this statement. I do not soften it.
   The facts are the facts, and a fact does not become less true because
   it is uncomfortable."
#}

{% macro plain_truth(statement, refusal) %}
{{ statement }}. {{ refusal }}.
{% endmacro %}

